en and Hong Kong Men -- tDislocating Punjabiyat: Gendered Mobilities among Indian Diasporas in Italy -- tV. Virtual Im/mobilities -- t"The World Has no Limits, so Why Should You?": Migration through Marriage in Times of Increasing Digitalization and Securitization of Borders -- tVirtual Im/mobilities: Three Ethnographic Examples of Socialised Media Usage, Civic Empowerment and Coded Publics -- tVI. Fixations within Mobility and Multilocality -- tThe Economic Diaspora: The Triple Helix of Im/mobilisation in the Hype about Migration and Development -- tThe Experience of Multilocal Living: Mobile Immobilities or Immobile Mobilities? -- tConceptual Notes on the Freedom of Movement and Bounded Mobilities -- tList of Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMobility is a keyword of late modernity that suggests an increasingly unrestrained and interconnected world of individual opportunities. However, as privileges enable some to live in a seemingly borderless world, others remain excluded and marginalized. Boundaries are created, modified and consolidated, particularly in times of hypermobility. Evidently, mobility is closely tied to immobility.This volume features ethnographic research that challenges the concept of mobility with regard to social inequalities and global hierarchies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEmigration and immigrationxSocial aspects. 4aBorder. 4aCultural Anthropology. 4aEthnography. 4aEthnology. 4aGlobalization. 4aImmobility. 4aInequality. 4aMigration. 4aPower Relations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aBorder.  aCultural Anthropology.  aEthnography.  aEthnology.  aGlobalization.  aImmobility.  aInequality.  aMigration.  aPower Relations.1 aBinah-Po